[Public Health Law §2312]
• pursuant to NY Education Law, NY licensed practitioners authorized to prescribe may dispense up to
a 72-hour supply, or more than 72-hour supply when:
o practicing in hospitals as defined in section twenty-eight hundred one of the Public Health Law;
o the dispensing of drugs is at no charge to their patients;
o their practices are situated ten miles or more from a registered pharmacy;
o the dispensing of drugs is in a clinic, infirmary or health service that is operated by or affiliated
with a post-secondary institution;
o the dispensing of drugs is due to a medical emergency as defined in NY State Education Law
Article 137 §6810(6);
o the dispensing of drugs that are diluted, reconstituted or compounded by a prescriber;
o the dispensing of allergenic extracts; or
o the dispensing of drugs pursuant to an oncological or acquired immunodeficiency syndrome
(AIDS) protocol:
▪ An oncologic protocol is written set of instructions to guide the administration
chemotherapy, immunotherapy, hormone therapy, targeted therapy to patients for the
treatment of cancer or tumors.
